This bill is not a silver bullet to end the youth vaping epidemic—which is why I have called for a ban on all e-cigarette products and comprehensive legislation to address the issue—but it is a good start. Now that it passed the House, I urge the Senate to take it up immediately.

With one in four high school students using e-cigarettes, and more vaping-related illnesses and deaths every day, it is long past time our government take on its moral responsibility to solve this problem.

There is broad, bipartisan agreement that kids should not be able to obtain dangerous e-cigarette products—whether in-person or online. That is why our bill closes loopholes that exempt online e-cigarette retailers from federal age verification requirements.

Today, the House took an important first step toward addressing the youth vaping epidemic by passing @RepArmstrongND's and my bill, the Preventing Online Sales of E-Cigarettes to Children Act. https://delauro.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/delauro-armstrong-e-cigarette-bill-passes-house-representatives …

On #WorldMentalHealthDay, we must continue the work to expand and guarantee access to affordable, quality mental healthcare, and Medicare for America will do just that.

And second, #Med4America also bans private contracting, which exacerbates barriers to mental healthcare. Currently, we have a two-tiered system where only the wealthy can afford care. #Med4America fixes that.

First, #Med4America gives mental health providers incentives to enter the pool. To increase care, we must increase the number of providers. Reimbursement rates are raised at least 30%, and our bill forgives 10% of student loan debt for each year the provider takes #Med4America.
Medicare for America would help solve this by guaranteeing universal, affordable, quality healthcare, and tearing down barriers to mental healthcare in two key ways. #MentalHealthAwarenessDay

Why so few? Too often, it is nearly impossible to find a mental health provider who accepts insurance. In a @NAMICommunicate survey, 1/3 of those seeking mental healthcare reported they could not find a single provider who took their insurance.

On #WorldMentalHealthDay, let's talk about how Congress can ensure that all Americans get the care and treatment they need. Right now, only around 40% of people suffering from a mental illness seek or get treatment. [thread]
